[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2-9 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, number of active care episodes, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, integration breadth across EHRs and external care partners, and human care-manager backstop overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is Tuesday morning at 9:42 AM. Eleanor is 73. Eleanor is sitting at her kitchen table with three voicemails saved on her phone, two appointment cards held to the refrigerator with magnets, a hospital discharge folder she received eleven days ago that she has only partially read, a printout of a referral order her primary care physician handed her a month ago, an envelope from her insurance company she has not opened, and a sticky note where she has been trying to keep track of who told her what about a follow-up CT scan that was supposed to happen "soon" after her hospitalization but which, eleven days later, has not been scheduled. Eleanor was hospitalized three weeks ago for a heart-failure exacerbation. She has, at last count, six clinicians involved in her care: her primary care physician (whom she has had for nineteen years and whom she trusts), the hospitalist who managed her admission and whose name she does not remember, the cardiologist whom she has seen once, the new pulmonologist she was referred to but has not yet seen because the office said the soonest available was in seven weeks, the home-health nurse who came twice in the first week after discharge and whom she liked, and the cardiac rehab program that her cardiologist mentioned but for which she has not yet been scheduled. The CT scan was ordered by the hospitalist to follow up on an incidental finding noted on the chest x-ray during admission. The order is in the hospital's chart. The PCP's chart, which is on a different EHR, does not have the order. The cardiologist's chart, on yet a third EHR, has a note that says "PCP to follow up on incidental finding, would defer to pulmonology." The pulmonology appointment has not happened. The CT scan has not happened. The incidental finding may be nothing; it may also be a small lung nodule that requires definitive diagnosis. The system, as a whole, does not know where Eleanor's CT scan request is. Eleanor does not know either. Eleanor's daughter, who lives two states away and who Eleanor has been calling on speakerphone whenever a confusing piece of paper arrives in the mail, also does not know.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is care coordination in the United States in 2026, and it is the area of healthcare where the gap between what the population needs and what the system delivers shows up most concretely as paper, voicemail, and dropped follow-ups. Eleanor's situation is not an outlier. It is the typical experience of any patient whose care has, for any reason, exceeded the capacity of a single clinician's mental and operational tracking. A patient with one chronic condition managed by their PCP can sometimes be coordinated by the PCP. A patient with one chronic condition plus an acute hospitalization plus two specialist referrals plus a home-health episode plus an insurance prior-authorization step plus a follow-up imaging study, ordered by a clinician on one EHR and supposed to be performed at a facility on a different EHR and reviewed by a clinician on a third EHR, is a patient whose care has exceeded what any single human can hold in their head, and the failure modes of that condition are well-documented and well-understood. Referrals do not get scheduled. Tests do not get done. Specialist notes do not get back to the PCP. Hospital discharge plans do not get followed because they are not visible to the outpatient team. Medication reconciliations do not happen at every transition. Patients miss follow-up appointments because they do not know they were supposed to have them, or because they know but cannot navigate the scheduling, or because the prior authorization the office sent the patient to handle is sitting in an unopened envelope on the kitchen table.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinical and economic consequences are large. A substantial fraction of hospital readmissions involve some form of post-discharge care-coordination failure: a follow-up appointment that did not happen, a medication reconciliation that did not occur, a specialist consultation that did not return its findings to the primary care team, a home-health episode that did not address the actual transition needs. <!-- TODO: verify; readmission causes have been studied extensively in the literature with the Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, the Project RED program, and similar transitional-care research showing meaningful reductions in readmission risk through coordinated post-discharge care; specific effect sizes vary by setting and population --> A meaningful share of avoidable healthcare cost in patients with serious or complex illness is concentrated in the gaps between care settings: between hospital and home, between specialty and primary care, between acute and post-acute, between active treatment and surveillance, between insurance benefit and clinical workflow. <!-- TODO: verify; the cost concentration in care-coordination gaps for high-cost, high-complexity patients is documented in CMS, Medicare Advantage, and accountable-care-organization analyses; specific figures vary --> The patients most affected are the patients with the most complex needs, which is to say the patients with the most chronic conditions, the most clinicians, the most care transitions, the most fragile social supports, and the least margin for navigating a complicated system. The patients most underserved by current coordination capacity are exactly the patients for whom uncoordinated care has the worst consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The professional answer to this problem, for the past two decades, has been care management. A care manager is typically a registered nurse, sometimes a social worker, sometimes a community health worker, who is assigned to a high-needs patient or panel and whose job is to do the work that, in Eleanor's case, no one is currently doing. The care manager calls Eleanor, follows up on the CT scan, makes sure the pulmonology appointment exists, calls the pulmonology office to ask if there is a sooner slot through a cancellation, talks to Eleanor's PCP about whether the CT scan could be done before the pulmonology visit, makes sure the home-health agency knows about the cardiac rehab plan, helps Eleanor open the insurance envelope and figure out whether the prior authorization for cardiac rehab has been approved, and (if Eleanor consents) calls Eleanor's daughter to keep her in the loop. Care management, when it works, works. The Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, the Project RED discharge program, the Boost program, the Medicare Chronic Care Management benefit, the Medicare Advantage care-management programs, and the various accountable-care-organization and integrated-delivery-system care-management initiatives have, in aggregate, demonstrated that coordinated post-discharge care, transitional care, and longitudinal care management for high-needs patients meaningfully reduce readmissions, ED visits, and total cost of care. <!-- TODO: verify; the Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, Project RED, Project BOOST, the CMS Chronic Care Management billing codes, and various ACO and Medicare Advantage care-management programs have published evidence of effect, with effect sizes varying by program design and population --> The professional consensus is that this is real work, that it works, and that it is dramatically under-supplied at population scale. Care managers are nurses or social workers, the workforce is finite, the case loads are typically thirty to seventy patients per care manager depending on the program intensity, and the patients on the case load are typically a small fraction of the patients who would benefit from care management. The patients who do not get care management are the patients sitting at the kitchen table on Tuesday morning with three voicemails and two appointment cards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The technological answer that has been tried for the past fifteen years is care-management software for care managers. These tools, when they work, give the care manager a structured workflow, a task list, an EHR integration, a way to log calls and document interventions, and a way to bill for the chronic-care-management codes. The tools, when they work, make the care manager more productive: a typical care manager using a structured care-management platform can manage a larger panel than one without. The tools do not, however, change the fundamental scaling problem: care management requires licensed clinicians, the workforce is finite, and the patient population that would benefit substantially exceeds the workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The technological answer that has begun to seem possible in the last few years is patient-facing conversational AI for routine care-coordination work. Not for replacing care managers; the licensed-clinician work of clinical judgment, clinical advocacy, motivational interviewing, and complex problem-solving across institutional boundaries cannot be replaced by a bot. For doing the routine, structured, follow-up-and-tracking work that consumes a meaningful fraction of a care manager's day and that, in the absence of a care manager, simply does not happen for the patients who most need it. Tracking whether the CT scan got scheduled. Surfacing the medication reconciliation list at the post-discharge follow-up. Reminding Eleanor about the cardiac rehab program. Walking Eleanor through the prior-authorization document and routing the document to the right human if it requires action. Answering Eleanor's question about which specialist's office she should call about the follow-up imaging when she has three different specialists. Letting Eleanor's daughter, with consent, see a summary of the open follow-up items. Keeping the digital version of Eleanor's care plan in sync across the three EHRs, the three patient portals, the home-health agency's system, the cardiac rehab program's system, and the insurance company's prior-authorization tracker. None of this is therapy. None of this is diagnosis. None of this is medical advice. All of this is the routine, high-volume, structured operational work of care coordination, and most of it is the kind of work that does not get done at population scale because there are not enough care managers to do it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about building, carefully, a care coordination assistant that does the routine operational work, escalates the cases that need clinical judgment to a licensed care manager, and operates with the patient as the primary user (with appropriate consent-gated visibility for caregivers and the care team). The architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental-health support bot) all converge here, and several entirely new patterns enter the picture: multi-EHR and multi-organization orchestration where the bot's "system of record" is, by necessity, a federated view across systems no single one of which the institution controls; longitudinal episode tracking where a "care episode" (post-hospitalization, active referral chain, transition between care settings, surveillance regimen for a serious condition) is the unit of state, not a single conversation; closed-loop tracking of operational items where the bot has to know whether a thing has happened and follow up if it has not; consent-gated caregiver visibility where the patient's daughter, husband, neighbor, or designated proxy can see and act on a curated portion of the patient's coordination state; tight integration with the licensed care-management workforce as a primary system component rather than a fallback; and operational tracking of items that may legitimately involve external organizations and external payers and external clinicians whose IT systems the institution has no read or write access to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that handles routine care-coordination operational work for patients with active care episodes: tracking referrals, tracking appointments and tests, surfacing care plan items, walking the patient through documents, answering operational questions about who to call about what, generating medication reconciliation prompts at transitions, surfacing prior-authorization status, alerting the patient (and with consent the caregiver and care team) about open items, and routing to a licensed care manager for the items that require clinical judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a care manager. The bot does not deliver clinical judgment, does not negotiate clinical exceptions with insurance, does not advocate for the patient in clinical disputes, does not provide complex problem-solving across institutional boundaries that is the legitimate work of a licensed care manager. The bot is the operational arm; the care manager is the judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinician. The bot does not provide medical advice, does not adjust the care plan, does not change appointments without confirming with the relevant clinician, does not provide clinical interpretation of results, and does not perform any function that requires a license.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a single-EHR product. The defining characteristic of care coordination is that the patient's care lives in multiple organizations' systems, none of which the institution fully controls. The bot's architecture has to operate across this federation rather than pretending it does not exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-shot product. A care episode is, by definition, a multi-conversation longitudinal entity. The bot's longitudinal-state architecture is the central engineering investment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a "set it and forget it" product. The bot's value depends on closed-loop operational tracking: knowing whether the CT scan was scheduled, whether the appointment was attended, whether the specialist's note came back, whether the prior authorization was approved. Without closed-loop tracking, the bot is a fancy reminder app.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the licensed care-management workforce. The bot extends the workforce's reach to patients the workforce cannot otherwise serve and frees the licensed care managers to focus on the cases that need clinical judgment. The bot does not replace the workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years. The multi-EHR and multi-organization integration work is multi-quarter. The episode-tracking-state-machine work is multi-quarter. The clinical-content investment for the care-coordination playbooks is multi-quarter. The licensed-care-manager workforce coordination is multi-quarter. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in cleverness of conversation. The value is in three places: the consistency of operational follow-through (the bot does not get tired at 4:30 PM on a Friday; the CT scan tracking continues over the weekend), the reach extension (patients who would not have received care management because the workforce capacity does not exist now receive a calibrated mix of bot and human), and the closed-loop discipline (the bot tracks whether things happened and follows up when they did not, which is the part of care management that is most labor-intensive and most underdone). A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on closed-loop completion of operational items, on referral conversion rates, on appointment completion rates, on time-to-resolution for open items, on care-manager case-load extension, and on longitudinal outcomes (readmission, ED utilization, time-to-treatment for surveillance items) is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
