Purpose: Append the Technology section

[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Across Federated Health Systems With Episode-Centric State And Closed-Loop Tracking
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Been Stuck, And What Changed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a humans-with-spreadsheets problem for almost all of its modern history. There are reasons for this, and the reasons are mostly structural, not technological.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first reason is that the unit of care-coordination work is not a single transaction; it is an episode. A referral is not "send a message"; it is "send a message, schedule a visit, complete the visit, return the consultation note, close the loop with the referring clinician, and follow up if any step in that chain stalls." A discharge is not "discharge the patient"; it is a multi-week multi-touch episode involving the post-discharge follow-up appointment, the medication reconciliation, the home-health initiation, the durable-medical-equipment delivery, the specialty follow-ups, the patient's understanding of the new care plan, the family's involvement, the prior authorization tracking for any new services, and the longitudinal surveillance for the conditions that triggered the admission. An imaging surveillance regimen for a small lung nodule is not "schedule one CT scan"; it is a multi-year longitudinal sequence of CTs at protocol intervals with structured comparison to the previous study, with the surveillance terminating at a defined endpoint based on whether the nodule grows, shrinks, or remains stable. The unit of state is the episode, and the episode has a multi-step state machine with branches, delays, retries, and exit conditions. Most patient-facing IT systems are not built around episodes; they are built around encounters, messages, or tasks, and they leak the episode state into spreadsheets, email threads, sticky notes, and care-manager mental models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second reason is that the data needed to manage an episode lives across organizational boundaries. The hospitalist's discharge order is in the hospital EHR. The PCP's note is in the PCP's EHR (often a different system). The specialist's consultation note is in the specialist's EHR (often a third). The home-health agency's documentation is in the home-health platform. The DME company's tracking is in the DME company's system. The insurance prior-authorization status is in the payer's portal. The pharmacy's prescription-fill status is in the pharmacy's system. The cardiac rehab program's enrollment status is in the rehab program's system. None of these systems share state automatically. Some of them exchange data via HL7 v2 messages or FHIR APIs where the relationships and consents permit. Most of them require manual synthesis by a human (the care manager, the patient, the family member). The consequence is that the question "where is Eleanor's CT scan?" does not have a single system that knows the answer; the answer is constructed by querying multiple systems and synthesizing the responses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The third reason is that the work is heterogeneous. A care manager's day involves operational follow-up, clinical advocacy, motivational interviewing, complex problem-solving, family communication, documentation, and billing. The operational follow-up part of the work is structured and high-volume. The clinical advocacy part of the work requires clinical judgment and licensure. The motivational interviewing part of the work requires interpersonal skill and behavioral-change expertise. Bundling all of these into a single human role is sensible from a continuity-of-relationship standpoint and inefficient from a workforce-utilization standpoint. The technology answer for the past fifteen years has been care-management software that organizes the human's day; the technology answer that has begun to seem possible is to have the bot do the operational follow-up part while the human focuses on the parts that require licensure, judgment, and relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The fourth reason is that the patient-side work has been mostly invisible to the system. The patient's role in their own care coordination is large: they are the only person who has full visibility into all of their care; they are the only one whose calendar has all of their appointments; they are the actor who picks up the phone and schedules the CT scan, opens the prior-authorization envelope, drives to the specialist's office, and reports symptoms back to the right clinician. The patient does this work whether or not the system supports it. When the patient cannot do this work (because of cognitive load, illness, age, social-determinant factors, language barriers, or simply not knowing how the system fits together), the work does not happen, and the consequences land on the patient. The technology answer for the patient side has historically been patient portals: useful for patients who can navigate them, marginally useful for patients who cannot, and almost entirely centered on individual encounters rather than episodes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed, again, is large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, structured conversation about an evolving operational situation, that can hold an episode's state in working memory, that can call tools to update or query that state across multiple systems, and that can route to a human when the situation requires clinical judgment. The bot does not solve the federation problem; the federation problem is solved (or partially solved) by HL7 v2, FHIR, point-to-point integrations, the occasional health information exchange, and (in the gaps) by care managers and patients. What the bot does is operate as a continuously-available, infinitely-patient, episode-aware patient interface that can do the routine operational work that the care manager would otherwise do, with the licensed care manager available for cases that need clinical judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what care coordination AI is and is not, because the category is muddled. The careful end of the spectrum is patient-facing operational support for active care episodes, with episode-aware state tracking, multi-system integration, closed-loop follow-up, and tight integration with a licensed care-management workforce. <!-- TODO: verify; products in this category include offerings from major EHR vendors as patient-portal extensions, integrated platforms deployed through health-system and payer channels, and standalone care-coordination platforms; specific product status varies --> The middle of the spectrum is general-purpose patient communication tools (appointment reminders, secure messaging, basic chatbots) used opportunistically for coordination tasks but without the episode-state-machine, closed-loop discipline, or workforce integration. The risky end of the spectrum is products that promise to "automate care management" without the operational rigor or licensed-clinician backstop, often pitched on the basis of cost savings rather than clinical effectiveness. This recipe is firmly in the careful end of the spectrum. The architectural decisions are, in part, decisions about which end of the spectrum the product lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care episodes, active referrals, scheduled and overdue appointments, active prescriptions and medications, active prior authorizations, recent discharge events, the patient's care team across organizations, the patient's stated preferences and consents, the patient's caregiver designations), access to a structured library of care-coordination playbooks (post-discharge transitions, referral management, surveillance regimens, prior-authorization navigation, medication reconciliation, durable-medical-equipment tracking, social-determinants navigation, condition-specific coordination workflows), and a careful set of tools for querying and updating the federated state across multiple EHRs, scheduling systems, payer systems, home-health platforms, and external care partners.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not a single conversation. It is a stream of episode-aware conversational interactions, sometimes initiated by the patient, sometimes initiated by the bot per a scheduled check-in tied to an episode milestone, sometimes triggered by an external event (a referral order arrives in the inbox, a discharge summary arrives, a specialist's note returns, an appointment is missed, a prior-authorization decision is rendered).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode initiation.** A care episode is created when a triggering event occurs: a hospital discharge, a referral order, an oncology treatment-plan kickoff, an active-surveillance regimen activation, a transition to home health, an enrollment in cardiac rehab, the start of a complex prior-authorization process, a chronic-care-management billable enrollment. The episode has a defined start, a defined expected duration (or the explicit "indefinite" flag for longitudinal regimens), a defined exit condition, and a state machine. The bot has access to the episode definition and the current state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational tracking and closed-loop follow-up.** For each episode, the bot tracks the operational items that the episode requires: appointments to be scheduled, appointments to be attended, tests to be performed, results to be received, notes to be returned, authorizations to be obtained, deliveries to be received, enrollments to be completed, medications to be picked up. For each item, the bot tracks the expected timeline, the current status, the responsible parties, and the next action. When an item stalls, the bot follows up: with the patient (the most common pattern), with the relevant office or external organization (where consent and integration permits), with the licensed care manager (where the situation has exceeded routine).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated coordination conversations.** The patient can engage at any time about coordination topics: "what are my open follow-up items?", "did the cardiology office get my MRI results?", "what is the status of the prior authorization for the pulmonary rehab program?", "I got a letter from my insurance, can you help me figure out what it says?", "I missed my appointment yesterday, what should I do?", "my daughter wants to know what specialists I am supposed to see next month, can you tell her?". The bot answers within scope using grounded queries against the federated state and the institution's care-coordination playbooks; the bot escalates outside scope (a clinical question, a complaint about clinical care, an active emergency, a complex insurance dispute requiring clinical advocacy).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Document handling support.** Patients receive care-coordination-relevant documents: discharge summaries, prior-authorization decisions, appointment reminders, lab result notifications, insurance correspondence. The bot can take a photo of a document, extract the operational content (using the OCR patterns from chapter 1), explain what the document is and what action it requires, and route to a human or to an automated workflow as appropriate. Skip this and a substantial fraction of patient-side coordination work is invisible to the bot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Bot-initiated check-ins tied to episode milestones.** At episode milestones (forty-eight hours after discharge, seven days after discharge, one day before a scheduled procedure, one day after a scheduled procedure, two weeks before an upcoming surveillance interval, one week before a prior-authorization expiration), the bot proactively reaches out with episode-appropriate content. Bot-initiated engagement is calibrated carefully to avoid the surveillance-flavor problem; the engagement is opt-in, opt-out-able, frequency-tunable, and channel-tunable per patient preference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver visibility, with consent.** Many high-needs patients have a designated caregiver (adult child, spouse, neighbor, formal care navigator). With explicit, granular, revocable consent, the caregiver can see a curated view of the patient's open coordination items, can receive alerts on key events, and can interact with the bot on the patient's behalf for a defined scope of operational tasks. Caregiver scope is more restrictive than patient scope; the bot does not deliver clinical content to caregivers and does not allow caregivers to make medical decisions for the patient unless legal authority (POA, healthcare proxy, guardianship) is documented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team visibility, with consent.** The patient's care team across organizations can receive structured summaries of the bot's coordination activity for that patient. Where the patient consents, the bot's coordination state is visible to the patient's PCP, specialists, and care manager. The visibility is structured and curated; the care team is not flooded with raw conversation logs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-manager workflow integration.** The licensed care-management workforce is the bot's clinical backstop. The care manager has a workflow tool that surfaces patients with open coordination items the bot has flagged for human attention, with the conversation context, the episode state, and the recommended action attached. The care manager's interventions are written back to the episode state so the bot stays current.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Federated state synthesis.** The bot's "answer" to "where is Eleanor's CT scan?" is constructed by querying the hospital EHR, the imaging-center scheduling system, the PCP's EHR, the patient's stated experience, and (where available) the FHIR APIs that connect them. The synthesis is structured: the bot composes a coherent answer that names the data sources, surfaces conflicts, and proposes a resolution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance.** The bot maintains conversation history, episode history, and stated patient preferences across years of care. Eleanor's interaction with the bot eighteen months from now references the patterns observed today; the bot does not pretend to remember as a person, but it does carry continuity that lets it operate efficiently across longitudinal care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when episode completes.** When an episode reaches its exit condition (the discharge transition is complete; the referral chain is closed; the surveillance regimen has terminated based on its protocol; the patient has graduated from active care management), the bot transitions out of episode-active mode while retaining the longitudinal record for future reference. New episodes spawn new episode-state instances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a helpful care-coordination assistant," and let it engage with patients about whatever they bring. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no episode state.** Without an explicit episode-state-machine architecture, the LLM relies on whatever conversation history fits in its context, which is not enough for a longitudinal care episode and certainly not enough for a patient with multiple concurrent episodes. The episode state has to be a first-class architectural object, persisted, queried, updated, and surfaced into the LLM's working context per turn.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no federated-state visibility.** The LLM, without tools, cannot query the hospital EHR, the PCP's EHR, the imaging center's scheduling system, the payer's prior-authorization tracker, the home-health platform, or the cardiac-rehab enrollment system. The model's answer to "where is the CT scan?" without tool use is a guess; the model's answer with tool use is a structured synthesis across federated state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no closed-loop tracking discipline.** Without an explicit closed-loop tracking subsystem, the LLM cannot know that it asked the patient about the CT scan three days ago and the patient said it had not happened yet and that the bot needs to follow up tomorrow if the imaging center has not scheduled by then. Closed-loop tracking is the difference between a reminder app and a coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents operational facts when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling "your CT scan is scheduled for Wednesday" because the conversation drift made that statement plausible is a bot delivering an operationally-false answer that the patient will act on. Every operational claim the bot makes has to be grounded in a tool-call result or a structured retrieval, with the source surfaced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no scope discipline about clinical content.** Care coordination conversations regularly touch clinical content (the patient asks about a symptom, asks about a result, asks about a medication side effect). The bot must explicitly stay in the operational lane and route clinical questions to the relevant clinician (the PCP, the specialist, the care manager, the on-call clinician, the triage line). The generalist LLM tries to be helpful and crosses the boundary regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent-gated visibility.** The patient's daughter can see some things and not others. The patient's PCP can see some things and not others. The patient's specialist can see some things and not others. The bot's data-disclosure logic is not "you are authenticated, here is everything"; it is a structured access-control model with patient-defined scopes per audience. A generalist LLM does not enforce this without explicit architectural support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-organization workflow.** The PCP is at one organization; the specialist is at another; the home-health agency is at a third; the payer is a fourth. The workflow integrations are different in each. The bot must know which organization is responsible for each step, which integration to use to query or update each, and how to handle cases where the integration is not available (which is the common case rather than the exceptional one).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to escalate.** Some situations are within the bot's scope (the patient asks for the next appointment date). Some are not (the patient describes symptoms that may indicate clinical deterioration; the patient is in active emotional crisis; the patient is in financial hardship that affects their ability to access care; the patient describes a clinical safety concern). The bot recognizes the boundary and routes to the licensed care manager (or, when appropriate, to a clinician, or, when appropriate, to crisis resources). The generalist LLM tries to handle everything and crosses boundaries regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems for date and timeline math.** "Two weeks after Tuesday" is something the LLM does sometimes, often, and unreliably. Date math, business-day math, holiday-aware math, and timezone-aware math are deterministic problems that should be solved by deterministic tools the LLM calls, not by the LLM itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has prior-authorization-status-arithmetic problems.** "Has the prior authorization for the cardiac rehab program been approved?" is a structured query against the payer's portal. The bot does not infer the answer; the bot calls the tool that queries the payer's system, surfaces the response, and (if the response is "pending" past the expected decision date) surfaces the next step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications around multi-organization data flow.** The conversation may involve data from multiple organizations under multiple BAAs, with different consent postures and different state-specific privacy implications. Sharing data across organizations requires deliberate design of the data-flow topology with legal and compliance review. Mental-health data in 42 CFR Part 2 organizations, substance-use data, HIV data, genetic data, and minor-treatment data all have specific cross-organizational handling rules.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social determinants and operational reality.** A patient who cannot afford the prior-authorization-required medication is not a patient who needs a polite note about following the medication regimen; the patient needs routing to the institution's financial-hardship support, the patient assistance program, the manufacturer's copay-assistance program, or a community resource. The bot has to recognize these patterns and route to the appropriate human or program; the generalist LLM treats the conversation as a knowledge-retrieval problem rather than an operational-routing problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of error compounding.** In a coordination workflow, an early error (an appointment recorded incorrectly, a referral attached to the wrong specialist, a CT scan ordered with the wrong protocol) propagates through the episode. The bot's discipline around verifying claims, surfacing conflicts, and escalating discrepancies is the architectural answer; the generalist LLM produces fluent answers that compound errors silently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to stop engaging.** Some patients want frequent contact; others want minimal contact. Some patients want bot contact only; others want the bot to handle everything but want a human for specific things. The engagement-frequency calibration is per-patient-stated-preference, episode-aware (post-discharge episodes have intentionally higher frequency), and channel-aware. The generalist LLM has no architectural support for this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That The Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis screening, warm handoff to licensed clinicians, companion-pattern avoidance. The care coordination assistant adds seven structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode state as architectural primitive.** The episode is the unit of state, with a defined start, defined expected duration, defined exit condition, and a state machine with branches, delays, retries, and exit conditions. The episode-state store is queried and updated on every relevant interaction. Skip the episode model and the bot is a context-window-bound chatbot rather than a coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-organization federated-state integration as architectural primitive.** The bot's "system of record" is a federation across multiple organizations' EHRs, scheduling systems, payer portals, home-health platforms, pharmacy systems, and external care-partner systems. The integration topology is per-organization-pair specific, with FHIR APIs where available, HL7 v2 where the relationships are older, point-to-point integrations where the partners have specific arrangements, and gracefully-degraded experiences where no integration is available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop tracking subsystem as architectural primitive.** Every operational item has a defined expected resolution timeline, a current status, a responsible party, and a next-action plan. When an item stalls, the bot follows up. The closed-loop tracking is what distinguishes a coordination assistant from a reminder app.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent-gated multi-audience visibility as architectural primitive.** The patient, the caregivers (with documented consent), the care team across organizations (with documented consent and per-organization scope), and the institutional care-management workforce each have curated views of the patient's coordination state. The visibility model is structured, granular, revocable, and audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-manager workflow integration as architectural primitive.** The licensed care manager is part of the architecture, not an afterthought. The care-manager workflow tool surfaces flagged patients with full episode and conversation context. Care-manager interventions are written back to the episode state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Document-extraction support as a routine input modality.** Patients arrive at conversations holding documents they do not understand. The bot's input pipeline includes document upload, OCR, structured extraction, and operational interpretation. This is a routine input modality, not an exceptional one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational-quality monitoring as architectural primitive.** The bot's evaluation metrics are operational: closed-loop completion rate, time-to-resolution for open items, referral conversion rate, appointment completion rate, prior-authorization approval rate, post-discharge follow-up completion rate, readmission rate, ED-utilization rate. These are evaluated per-cohort and per-episode-type, and the patterns drive operational improvement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail, mental-health-style crisis screening on every utterance (because care-coordination conversations sometimes surface psychiatric or self-harm content), warm handoff infrastructure for the cases that need humans.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care-Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically hard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration scope is large and is not under the institution's control.** A typical patient with a complex care episode interacts with five to fifteen organizations across the episode. The institution's IT can integrate cleanly with its own EHR; integration with external EHRs depends on the technical readiness and cooperation of the external organization. FHIR APIs help; FHIR APIs do not solve the problem. Some integrations are structured (FHIR), some are unstructured (HL7 v2 ADT feeds, faxed PDF discharge summaries, scanned referral orders), and some do not exist (the patient's prior authorization status at a payer the institution does not have an integration with). The bot's integration topology is gracefully degraded for cases where the integration is missing; the bot still helps the patient even when the bot cannot directly query the relevant external system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The episode-type taxonomy is large and is institution-specific.** Post-discharge transitions, oncology treatment-plan episodes, transplant care episodes, prenatal-care episodes, surgical episodes, surveillance episodes (cancer, lung-nodule, aneurysm, valve disease), chronic-condition longitudinal episodes, behavioral-health treatment episodes, end-of-life and palliative-care episodes, pediatric chronic-care episodes, complex-care-management enrollment episodes, social-care-coordination episodes for high-need-low-resource patients. Each episode type has its own playbook, its own milestone schedule, its own consent considerations, its own clinical risk pattern, and its own appropriate-bot-vs-care-manager calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient-population stratification matters enormously.** A relatively well, English-speaking, computer-literate patient with one chronic condition and a single PCP needs a much lighter-touch coordination assistant than a frail, multi-comorbid, non-English-speaking patient with limited family support, complicated insurance, and a recent ICU admission. The bot's calibration per population segment is part of the architectural design, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The care-manager-workforce integration is operationally complex.** Care managers have caseloads, schedules, working hours, on-call rotations, and vacation. The bot's escalation-to-care-manager logic has to know which care manager owns the patient, what the care manager's current capacity looks like, what the appropriate escalation channel is for the urgency level, and what happens when the primary care manager is unavailable. The platform's licensed-clinician workforce is part of the operations, not just a deployment artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The consent architecture is harder than in the previous bots.** A care-coordination conversation may legitimately involve information from multiple organizations under multiple BAAs. Sharing across organizations requires deliberate consent. State-specific privacy considerations may apply (mental-health records in some states, substance-use records under 42 CFR Part 2, HIV records, genetic records, minor-treatment records). The patient's caregiver designations, the patient's care-team-sharing consents per organization, and the patient's bot-engagement preferences all interact. The consent model is granular, revocable, and audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** The patients with the highest unmet care-coordination need are often the patients who face linguistic, cultural, and digital-literacy barriers in the existing system. A bot that operates only in English at one reading level on one channel is a bot that perpetuates existing care-coordination disparities. The bot's multilingual deployment, channel diversity (SMS, voice for patients without smartphones, in-person staff-mediated for patients without digital access), and reading-level calibration are architectural commitments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family and caregiver involvement is heterogeneous.** Some patients have engaged adult children who would happily help; some patients have estranged family they do not want involved; some patients have a paid private caregiver; some patients have a community-volunteer caregiver. The bot's caregiver model handles all of these patterns and gives the patient explicit control.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinant intersections are large and are routinely the actual coordination obstacle.** The CT scan does not get scheduled because the patient does not have a way to get to the imaging center. The medication does not get filled because the patient cannot afford the copay. The post-discharge follow-up does not happen because the patient does not have childcare for the visit. The bot's integration with the institution's social-determinants screening, financial-hardship support, transportation benefits, food-security resources, and care-navigation pathways turns out to be one of the highest-value architectural investments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is multi-quarter to multi-year work.** Reducing readmissions, reducing ED utilization, reducing total cost of care, improving timely-treatment metrics, improving patient-experience metrics: these are observable on quarterly to annual timelines. Most teams underestimate how long the analysis takes and how many confounders are involved. Mitigation: realistic expectations about timeline, careful study design, recognition that engaged-patient outcomes are not random-sample outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningful and is concentrated at the integration boundaries.** A bot that "tracks" a CT scan and the CT scan does not happen and the lung nodule grows into a clinical problem is a bot whose tracking apparently failed. The institutional liability framework for the bot covers what the bot is responsible for tracking, what the patient is responsible for, what the clinician is responsible for, and how missed-tracking failures are surfaced. The institutional malpractice insurer is part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot-and-care-manager interface is the operational heart.** A bot that escalates effectively to a care manager whose workload is sized appropriately, with full episode context attached, in a workflow tool the care manager actually uses, with clean write-back to the episode state, is a deployment that works. A bot that escalates to a care manager whose case load is already crushing, in a workflow the care manager does not use, with poor context, with no write-back, is a deployment whose value evaporates rapidly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR APIs have matured for the data classes that matter.** US Core, USCDI, and the FHIR Bulk Data API specifications cover the core data classes the bot needs (Patient, Condition, MedicationStatement, AllergyIntolerance, Encounter, ServiceRequest, Appointment, DocumentReference, CarePlan, CareTeam, Goal, Communication, Task). <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR US Core, USCDI versions, and Bulk Data API specifications continue to evolve; specific support varies by EHR vendor and customer deployment --> Major EHR vendors support FHIR APIs at varying levels of completeness. The integration topology is per-vendor and per-deployment specific, but the standards have matured to the point where multi-EHR integration is feasible without bespoke per-customer work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and QHIN-mediated exchange enable nationwide patient matching and document exchange.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, with the Qualified Health Information Networks operating under it, has begun to deliver on the promise of nationwide health information exchange. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA went live in late 2023 with the first QHINs designated; the network has continued to grow with operational effects on patient-record exchange varying by participation and use case --> For care-coordination assistants, this matters most for the historical-record-fetching that is part of episode initiation and for the patient-matching across organizations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop referral tracking has standardized vocabulary.** The HL7 Da Vinci Project, AHRQ, and major EHR vendors have converged on patterns for closed-loop referral tracking with structured status codes and structured outcome notes. <!-- TODO: verify; the HL7 Da Vinci Project has published implementation guides for closed-loop referrals and several other care-coordination workflows; specific vendor support varies --> The bot's closed-loop tracking benefits from this standardization where it is implemented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination playbooks are well-codified for many episode types.** Project RED for hospital discharge, the Coleman Care Transitions Intervention, the BOOST program, the AHRQ care-coordination toolkits, the CMS chronic-care-management billing-code workflows, and a growing body of condition-specific playbooks (post-acute-MI care, post-stroke care, post-surgical care, oncology survivorship care, transplant care). <!-- TODO: verify; the Project RED, Coleman CTI, BOOST, AHRQ care-coordination toolkits, and CMS CCM workflows are extensively documented; institutional implementations vary --> Bot-deployable playbooks are curated from these sources by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Document-AI is mature enough for routine care-coordination documents.** The OCR and structured-extraction patterns from chapter 1 work for discharge summaries, prior-authorization decisions, insurance correspondence, and lab-result notifications. The integration with the bot's input pipeline is a routine extension, not exotic engineering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system coordination well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that query and update federated state, that run closed-loop tracking, that route to care managers, and that post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-licensed-care-manager deployment is the dominant pattern.** Most evidence-based deployments run a hybrid model: bot for routine operational work and tracking, licensed care manager for clinical advocacy, complex problem-solving, and motivational interviewing. The evidence base for hybrid deployments is stronger than for either AI-alone or human-alone deployments. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for hybrid AI-plus-care-manager deployments is documented in studies of programs from major payers and integrated delivery systems, with effect sizes varying -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is heterogeneous.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination platforms with patient-facing assistants, EHR integration, payer-portal integration, and care-manager workflow tools. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for the multi-EHR integration and (sometimes) the licensed-care-manager workforce, integrate with the institution's existing care-management infrastructure, and customize the playbooks per institutional clinical-leadership signoff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reimbursement supports some of the work.** Medicare's Chronic Care Management codes, Transitional Care Management codes, Principal Care Management codes, and various Medicare Advantage and ACO arrangements provide reimbursement for some of the licensed-care-manager work the bot supports. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS billing codes for CCM, TCM, PCM, and behavioral-health integration continue to evolve; specific payment rates and documentation requirements vary --> The bot's value-prop includes both direct outcome improvements and the capacity-extension that lets the institution serve more billable patients with the same workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
